Actually , if there is no running blocking thread in tomcat thread pool , it is normally that close the sever immediately when you stop the  server.


you can use the following code snippet for test .
```java
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestController;

@RestController
public class ShutdownController {

    private volatile boolean shutdownRequested = false;

    @GetMapping(&quot;/graceful-shutdown-test&quot;)
    public String gracefulShutdownTest() {
        // Simulate a long-running process
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; 10; i++) {
            if (shutdownRequested) {
                return &quot;Shutdown requested. Cleaning up...&quot;;
            }

            try {
                Thread.sleep(1000); // Simulate some work
            } catch (InterruptedException e) {
                Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
            }
        }

        return &quot;Process completed successfully!&quot;;
    }

    // Endpoint to trigger a graceful shutdown
    @GetMapping(&quot;/trigger-shutdown&quot;)
    public String triggerShutdown() {
        shutdownRequested = true;
        return &quot;Shutdown requested. It may take some time to complete ongoing tasks.&quot;;
    }
}

```

try to  request the REST API , and when it is blocking , close the server , it would wait  for all the thread is done which is in tomcat thread pool . that is graceful shutdown

